<subSubSection lastPageId="43" lastPageNumber="279" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,1267,2013]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicName authority="(Brady, 1910)" baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[151,572,1267,1293]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,414,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Microthalestris gracilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brady, G. S." box="[426,564,1267,1293]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="497 - 594" refId="ref68877" refString="Brady, G. S. (1910) Die marinen Copepoden der Deutschen Sudpolar Expedition 1901 - 1903. I. Ueber die Copepoden der Stamme Harpacticoida, Cyclopoida, Notodelphyoida und Caligoida. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition, 11 (= Zoologie 3), 497 - 594." type="journal article" year="1910">Brady, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[577,704,1267,1293]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[577,704,1267,1293]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to a close-knit group of subantarctic species characterized by the position of the inner seta on P1 enp-1 which originates from the middle third of the segment. This subantarctic group includes 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[329,455,1339,1365]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[329,455,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Scott, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[471,783,1339,1365]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[471,624,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. antarctica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, T." box="[642,774,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="521 - 599" refId="ref79390" refString="Scott, T. (1912) The Entomostraca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition, 1902 - 1904. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 48, 521 - 599, pls. I - XIV. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800015829" type="journal article" year="1912">Scott, 1912</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[792,923,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[792,923,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pallares, 1982)" baseAuthorityName="Pallares" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[939,1249,1339,1365]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[939,1060,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. costata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pallares, R. E." box="[1077,1241,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="3 - 39" refId="ref77142" refString="Pallares, R. E. (1982) Copepodos harpacticoides marinos de Tierra del Fuego (Argentina). IV. Bahia Thetis. Contribucion cientifica del Centro de Investigacion de Biologia marina, Buenos Aires, 186, 3 - 39, pls. I - XII." type="journal article" year="1982">Pallares, 1982</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1259,1389,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1259,1389,1339,1365]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="santacruzensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. santacruzensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[324,415,1375,1401]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[324,415,1375,1401]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[472,617,1375,1401]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[472,617,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[626,717,1375,1401]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[626,717,1375,1401]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
In all other members of the genus the inner seta of P1 enp-1 is situated further proximally, at around 25% the length of the inner margin of the segment. Interestingly, the latter condition is also displayed by 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pallares, 1982)" baseAuthorityName="Pallares" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[491,790,1447,1473]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuta" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[491,606,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. minuta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pallares, R. E." box="[620,782,1447,1473]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="3 - 39" refId="ref77142" refString="Pallares, R. E. (1982) Copepodos harpacticoides marinos de Tierra del Fuego (Argentina). IV. Bahia Thetis. Contribucion cientifica del Centro de Investigacion de Biologia marina, Buenos Aires, 186, 3 - 39, pls. I - XII." type="journal article" year="1982">Pallares, 1982</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[797,925,1447,1473]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[797,925,1447,1473]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[993,1178,1447,1473]" country="Argentina" name="Tierra del Fuego - Antartida e Islas del Atlantico Sur" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Tierra del Fuego</collectingRegion>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1233,1436,1447,1473]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="campbelliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1233,1436,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">M. campbelliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,241,1483,1509]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,241,1483,1509]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from Campbell Island, suggesting the independent colonization of the subantarctic region by two different lineages. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[257,521,1519,1545]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[257,521,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Microthalestris gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[527,655,1519,1545]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[527,655,1519,1545]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is known from a single female collected in the Baie de l’Observatoire (Observatory Bay) along the northern shore of the 
<collectingRegion box="[720,784,1555,1581]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Golfe</collectingRegion>
du Morbihan in the Kerguelen (
<bibRefCitation author="Brady, G. S." box="[1144,1337,1554,1581]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="497 - 594" refId="ref68877" refString="Brady, G. S. (1910) Die marinen Copepoden der Deutschen Sudpolar Expedition 1901 - 1903. I. Ueber die Copepoden der Stamme Harpacticoida, Cyclopoida, Notodelphyoida und Caligoida. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition, 11 (= Zoologie 3), 497 - 594." type="journal article" year="1910">Brady 1910: 513</bibRefCitation>
; Textfig. VIII). A second record by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jayabarathi, R." box="[457,668,1591,1618]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" refId="ref73932" refString="Jayabarathi, R. (2016) Spatial Heterogeneity and Biodiversity of Harpacticoid Copepods and other Meiofaunal Associates within the Seagrass Patches of South Andaman. Ph. D. dissertation, Pondicherry University, Port Blair, vii + 205 pp." type="book" year="2016">Jayabarathi (2016)</bibRefCitation>
from seagrass beds in South Andaman is highly questionable. The original description includes illustrations of the antennule, P1, P2, P5 and caudal rami but is deficient in many aspects. The armature is unknown for P3–P4 except for 
<bibRefCitation author="Brady, G. S." box="[793,963,1663,1689]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="497 - 594" refId="ref68877" refString="Brady, G. S. (1910) Die marinen Copepoden der Deutschen Sudpolar Expedition 1901 - 1903. I. Ueber die Copepoden der Stamme Harpacticoida, Cyclopoida, Notodelphyoida und Caligoida. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition, 11 (= Zoologie 3), 497 - 594." type="journal article" year="1910">Brady’s (1910)</bibRefCitation>
dubious claim that their distal endopodal segments have only three elements. The P2 is shown to have two inner setae on exp-3 which is also questionable. Since within the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Willen" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[343,527,1735,1761]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Parastenheliidae</taxonomicName>
this condition is only found in members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monard" authorityYear="1935" box="[1024,1158,1735,1761]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Thalestrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1024,1158,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Thalestrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gee" authorityYear="2006" box="[1214,1303,1735,1760]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Foweya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1214,1303,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Foweya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[1318,1402,1735,1761]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="21.[151,170,491,518]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="TABLE 1. Swimming leg armature formulae (P1–P5) of parastenheliid species (b = endopodal lobe of baseoendopod; enp = endopod; e, exp = exopod; S = number of exopodal segments; – = missing data). *: species inquirendae; **: indeterminable forms in need of thorough redescription. Genus abbreviations: Pa. = Parastenhelia, Par. = Paraleptomesochra, Pe. = Penicillicaris, Po. = Porirualia, Ps. = Psammoleptomesochra," httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/49CE6674FFD6FF8BFF51D2F3E00FFD95" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" tableUuid="49CE6674FFD6FF8BFF51D2F3E00FFD95">Table 1</tableCitation>
) it may indicate that 
<bibRefCitation author="Brady, G. S." box="[356,526,1771,1797]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" pagination="497 - 594" refId="ref68877" refString="Brady, G. S. (1910) Die marinen Copepoden der Deutschen Sudpolar Expedition 1901 - 1903. I. Ueber die Copepoden der Stamme Harpacticoida, Cyclopoida, Notodelphyoida und Caligoida. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition, 11 (= Zoologie 3), 497 - 594." type="journal article" year="1910">Brady’s (1910)</bibRefCitation>
illustration is either based on an observational error or in reality refers to P3 or P4. Alternatively, the possibility that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[567,681,1807,1833]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[567,681,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a member of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gee" authorityYear="2006" box="[957,1046,1807,1832]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Foweya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[957,1046,1807,1832]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">Foweya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be excluded but this would require information on the male and the sexual dimorphism in this species. Another unusual feature of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1322,1437,1843,1869]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[1322,1437,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the endopodal lobe of P5 which is remarkably small and displays only four setae. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[1120,1279,1879,1905]" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" refId="ref75271" refString="Lang, K. (1948) Monographie der Harpacticiden. Vols. 1 - 2. Hakan Ohlsson, Lund, 1682 pp." type="book" year="1948">Lang’s (1948)</bibRefCitation>
concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Chislenko" authorityYear="1967" baseAuthorityName="Fischer" baseAuthorityYear="1860" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">P. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grouped together all the various forms in which the middle segment of P1 exopod was at least four times as long as broad, with the exception of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[559,673,1951,1977]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="42" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[559,673,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="278">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which was maintained as a distinct species mainly on the difference in the site of origin of the inner seta of P1 enp-2 and the shape of the female P5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,150,1307]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, T." box="[199,388,150,177]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="521 - 599" refId="ref79390" refString="Scott, T. (1912) The Entomostraca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition, 1902 - 1904. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 48, 521 - 599, pls. I - XIV. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800015829" type="journal article" year="1912">Scott (1912: 561</bibRefCitation>
; Plate IV, figs. 25–33) described a second subantarctic species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1098,1239,151,176]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[1098,1239,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from Scotia Bay (
<geoCoordinate box="[160,303,187,213]" degrees="60" direction="south" minutes="43" orientation="latitude" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" precision="15" seconds="42" value="-60.728333">60°43’42” S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[317,470,187,213]" degrees="44" direction="west" minutes="38" orientation="longitude" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" precision="15" seconds="33" value="-44.6425">44°38’33” W</geoCoordinate>
) in the South 
<collectingCountry box="[633,805,187,213]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Orkney Islands</collectingCountry>
and compared the female (males are unknown) with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gurney, R." box="[251,474,222,249]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="451 - 577" refId="ref72332" refString="Gurney, R. (1927) XXXIII. Report on the Crustacea: - Copepoda (littoral and semi-parasitic). Zoological results of the Cambridge expedition to the Suez Canal, 1924. Transactions of the zoological Society of London, 22, 451 - 577, figs. 108 - 168, tab. 35. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1927. tb 00207. x" type="journal article" year="1927">Gurney (1927: 544)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[649,790,223,248]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[649,790,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appeared to be identical with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1130,1244,223,249]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[1130,1244,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 56" refId="ref75124" refString="Lang, K. (1934) Marine Harpacticiden von der Campbell-Insel und einigen anderen sudlichen Inseln. Acta Universitatis lundensis, New Series, Avd. 2, 30 (14), 1 - 56." type="journal article" year="1934">Lang (1934: 23)</bibRefCitation>
formally treated them as synonyms but neither author gave a justification for this claim. This course of action appears premature since significant differences can be observed in the morphology of P1 (length of exopod, in particular exp-2; length of claws on enp-2) and P5 (shape of exopod), both of which were dismissed as irrelevant by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[187,322,367,393]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 56" refId="ref75124" refString="Lang, K. (1934) Marine Harpacticiden von der Campbell-Insel und einigen anderen sudlichen Inseln. Acta Universitatis lundensis, New Series, Avd. 2, 30 (14), 1 - 56." type="journal article" year="1934">Lang (1934</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[334,405,367,393]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref75162" refString="Lang, K. (1936 a) Copepoda Harpacticoida. Further zoological Results of the Swedish Antarctic Expedition 1901 - 1903 under the Direction of Dr Otto Nordenskjold, 3 (3), 1 - 68." type="journal article" year="1936">1936a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[418,478,367,393]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" refId="ref75271" refString="Lang, K. (1948) Monographie der Harpacticiden. Vols. 1 - 2. Hakan Ohlsson, Lund, 1682 pp." type="book" year="1948">1948</bibRefCitation>
). Although an unusual degree of intra-individual and intra-population variability has been recorded in the armature patterns of P2–P 
<quantity box="[688,732,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
some species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sewell" authorityYear="1940" box="[928,1085,403,429]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[928,1085,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Parastenhelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1103,1143,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">e.g.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Mielke, W." box="[1152,1299,403,429]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref75739" refString="Mielke, W. (1974) Eulitorale Harpacticoidea (Copepoda) von Spitzbergen. Mikrofauna des Meeresbodens, 37, 1 - 52" type="journal article" year="1974">Mielke 1974</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mielke, W." box="[1311,1368,403,429]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="157 - 167" refId="ref75763" refString="Mielke, W. (1990) A Parastenhelia species from Bahia Lapataia, Ushuaia, Tierra del Fuego (Argentina). Microfauna marina, 6, 157 - 167." type="journal article" year="1990">1990</bibRefCitation>
) such variability is not expressed in the morphology of either P1 or P5. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[868,1053,440,467]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref75162" refString="Lang, K. (1936 a) Copepoda Harpacticoida. Further zoological Results of the Swedish Antarctic Expedition 1901 - 1903 under the Direction of Dr Otto Nordenskjold, 3 (3), 1 - 68." type="journal article" year="1936">Lang (1936a: 53</bibRefCitation>
; Figs 36–37) reported 
<specimenCount box="[1302,1436,440,466]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
from Berkeley Sound, Port Louis in the 
<collectingCountry box="[611,796,476,502]" name="Falkland Islands" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Falkland Islands</collectingCountry>
which he attributed to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brady" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1063,1178,476,502]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[1063,1178,476,502]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. His illustration of the P1 leaves no doubt that he was dealing with the geographically closer 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[973,1118,514,539]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[973,1118,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since it is fully compatible in the relative lengths of its rami, exp-2 and claws on exp-3 with 
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, T." box="[921,1082,549,575]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="521 - 599" refId="ref79390" refString="Scott, T. (1912) The Entomostraca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition, 1902 - 1904. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 48, 521 - 599, pls. I - XIV. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800015829" type="journal article" year="1912">Scott’s (1912)</bibRefCitation>
original description. 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, G. M." pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="93 - 116" refId="ref81234" refString="Thomson, G. M. (1883) On the New Zealand Copepoda. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, New Series, 15, 93 - 116, pls. V - XI." type="journal article" year="1883">Thomson (1883</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, G. M." box="[233,290,586,612]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref81273" refString="Thomson, G. M. (1913) The natural history of Otago Harbour and the adjacent sea, together with a record of the researches carried on at the Portobello marine fish-hatchery: Part I. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, new series, 45, 225 - 251, pl. X." type="journal article" year="1913">1913</bibRefCitation>
) recorded numerous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Claus" authorityYear="1862" box="[534,646,586,612]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Thalestridae" genus="Thalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[534,646,586,612]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Thalestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[895,963,586,612]" country="New Zealand" name="Otago" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Otago</collectingRegion>
Harbour, Dunedin in the South Island of 
<collectingCountry box="[151,302,622,649]" name="New Zealand" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and assigned them to Claus’s (1863) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Monard" authorityYear="1928" box="[730,855,622,648]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forficula">
<emphasis box="[730,855,622,648]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">T. forficula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Brady, G. S." box="[970,1121,622,649]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="31 - 54" refId="ref68770" refString="Brady, G. S. (1899) On the marine Copepoda of New Zealand. Transactions of the zoological Society of London, 15 (2), 31 - 54, pls. IX - XIII. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1899. tb 00018. x" type="journal article" year="1899">Brady (1899)</bibRefCitation>
who found it abundantly in the same location]. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[380,515,659,685]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 56" refId="ref75124" refString="Lang, K. (1934) Marine Harpacticiden von der Campbell-Insel und einigen anderen sudlichen Inseln. Acta Universitatis lundensis, New Series, Avd. 2, 30 (14), 1 - 56." type="journal article" year="1934">Lang (1934</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[530,600,659,686]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref75162" refString="Lang, K. (1936 a) Copepoda Harpacticoida. Further zoological Results of the Swedish Antarctic Expedition 1901 - 1903 under the Direction of Dr Otto Nordenskjold, 3 (3), 1 - 68." type="journal article" year="1936">1936a</bibRefCitation>
) initially listed Thomson’s record under the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lang" baseAuthorityYear="1936" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="forficula" variety="littoralis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Parastenhelia forficula</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[303,399,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">littoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and subsequently, again without giving any specific justification, classified it as conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lang 1948)" baseAuthorityName="Lang" baseAuthorityYear="1948" box="[212,486,732,758]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[212,329,733,758]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. spinosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, K." box="[348,478,732,758]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" refId="ref75271" refString="Lang, K. (1948) Monographie der Harpacticiden. Vols. 1 - 2. Hakan Ohlsson, Lund, 1682 pp." type="book" year="1948">Lang 1948</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wells, J. B. J. &amp; Hicks, G. R. F. &amp; Coull, B. C." box="[500,720,732,758]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="151 - 184" refId="ref82409" refString="Wells, J. B. J., Hicks, G. R. F. &amp; Coull, B. C. (1982) Common harpacticoid copepods from New Zealand harbours and estuaries. New Zealand Journal of Zoology, 9, 151 - 184. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014223.1982.10423847" type="journal article" year="1982">
Wells 
<emphasis box="[574,635,732,758]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">et al.</emphasis>
(1982)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested that the 
<collectingRegion box="[950,1018,732,758]" country="New Zealand" name="Otago" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Otago</collectingRegion>
Harbour material may belong to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wells, Hicks &amp; Coull" baseAuthorityYear="1982" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Porirualia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megarostrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. megarostrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but were unable to make a firm recommendation for this assignment on morphological grounds (see below). 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, G. M." box="[242,448,805,831]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="93 - 116" refId="ref81234" refString="Thomson, G. M. (1883) On the New Zealand Copepoda. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, New Series, 15, 93 - 116, pls. V - XI." type="journal article" year="1883">Thomson’s (1883)</bibRefCitation>
illustrations (Plate X, figs 16–21) show several similarities with the original description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[181,321,842,867]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[181,321,842,867]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including (a) the general outline and proportional segmental lengths of the female antennule; (b) P1 exopod with elongate exp-2; (c) P1 endopod showing similar L:W ratio for enp-1; claws on enp-2 elongate as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and (d) female P5 setation and general shape of exopod. Based on these similarities we consider it likely that 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, G. M." box="[199,405,951,977]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="93 - 116" refId="ref81234" refString="Thomson, G. M. (1883) On the New Zealand Copepoda. Transactions and Proceedings of the New Zealand Institute, New Series, 15, 93 - 116, pls. V - XI." type="journal article" year="1883">Thomson’s (1883)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Monard" authorityYear="1928" box="[412,535,951,977]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forficula">
<emphasis box="[412,535,951,977]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">T. forficula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[665,807,952,977]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[665,807,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only main difference being the position of the inner seta on P1 enp-1 which inserts more distally. The female antennule of Thomson’s specimens was described as 8- segmented but reinterpretation of his illustration (Plate X, fig. 17) suggests it has nine segments (as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1279,1420,1025,1050]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[1279,1420,1025,1050]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">P. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The presence of four setae on the proximal segment indicates that it represents the second segment and that the real first segment was not observed or lost during dissection. The aesthetasc that originates from a ventral pedestal of the fourth segment is shown to insert on the anterodistal corner of this segment (in reality the fifth) in Thomson’s drawing; this can be explained by assuming that the author observed the antennule in dorsal aspect. Based on the arguments above, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Scott, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[354,798,1207,1233]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Miraciidae" genus="Microthalestris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarctica" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[354,646,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">Microthalestris antarctica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, T." box="[660,790,1207,1233]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" pagination="521 - 599" refId="ref79390" refString="Scott, T. (1912) The Entomostraca of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition, 1902 - 1904. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 48, 521 - 599, pls. I - XIV. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800015829" type="journal article" year="1912">Scott, 1912</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[804,932,1207,1233]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[804,932,1207,1233]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is here reinstated as a valid species. It is very close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pallares" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[245,363,1244,1269]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Parastenheliidae" genus="Parastenhelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Harpacticoida" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[245,363,1244,1269]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">M. costata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[370,499,1244,1270]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[370,499,1244,1270]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the morphology of the P1 and the foliaceaous 
<specimenCount box="[1053,1074,1244,1270]" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
P5 exopod but differs from it in the armature of the distal endopodal segment of P4 (
<tableCitation box="[736,820,1280,1306]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="21.[151,170,491,518]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="TABLE 1. Swimming leg armature formulae (P1–P5) of parastenheliid species (b = endopodal lobe of baseoendopod; enp = endopod; e, exp = exopod; S = number of exopodal segments; – = missing data). *: species inquirendae; **: indeterminable forms in need of thorough redescription. Genus abbreviations: Pa. = Parastenhelia, Par. = Paraleptomesochra, Pe. = Penicillicaris, Po. = Porirualia, Ps. = Psammoleptomesochra," httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/49CE6674FFD6FF8BFF51D2F3E00FFD95" pageId="43" pageNumber="279" tableUuid="49CE6674FFD6FF8BFF51D2F3E00FFD95">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
